properties.documentation: Pertains to public structures and activities intended to remove or treat stormwater. Two tiers of BMP types exist, detailed and generalized.
A DryWell is an Inflow Control that shunts water from an impervious area into the ground. There is usually no chance for this water to get back into the model.
A Green Roof is an Inflow Control that absorbs water via abstraction.
An Inflow Control is a device applied to a Model Element to reduce or attenuate the flow of water in a Model.
A Link is a structural, directed connection between two Nodes.

A Node is a significant point in a model and can represent a manhole, a flow entry point, a grade break, a change in material, and other structurally significant changes in the flow of water in the physical network.
Nonstructural: any activity intended to reduce pollutants through education, waste reduction and treatment programs. Quantification of effects are usually difficult to identify.
An Orifice is a Link that represents a sharp constriction in the flow of water in a Model.
An Outfall is a Node that represents where water in the Model is released to a receiving water, a treatment plant, or the ground.
A Pipe is a Link that represents a physical pipe (usually cylindrical, but can also be of different shapes) that provides open channel flow when not full and presurrized, closed pipe flow when full.
A Pipe Condition is a collection of attributes describing a Pipe's structural and operational characteristics.
A Pipe Geometry is the geometric specification of a Pipe Shape, from the bottom to the top of the cross section.
A Pipe Shape is the cross-sectional geometric description Pipes have for determining their hydraulic characteristics.

A Pump is a Link that represents a pump station between two Nodes. The upstream Node is where the pump station takes in water, and the downstream Node is where the pump station either discharges or delivers flow to a pressurized Pipe.

A Pump Curve is a pair of values dictating the flow a pump will deliver based on either the dynamic head between the upstream and downstram Nodes of a Pump or based on the absolute head at the upstream Node of a Pump.
A StorageNode is a Node that either has significantly more area per unit of depth than a normal Node or has a varying area per unit of depth.

Structural: a device intended to remove or delay either flow or contaminants using either treatment, disposal, or storage. Examples include swales, on-site inflow controls, detention facilities, and UICs, Control levels expressed in terms of percent reduction, volume removed, or effluent concentration.
A UIC is an underground injection control (sump) that usually directs water from a subcatchment into the ground. The water is considered lost from the Model when it is run.
A UIC Well is a component of a UIC
A Weir is a Link that blocks flow from an incoming Link up to a certain depth.
